    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-04-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-04-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="486" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d486">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Clay</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Seward</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 78.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-04-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 24, 1865.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> It becomes my painful duty to inform you
                            that this morning at half-past twelve o’clock his Imperial Highness the
                            Grand Duke Héritier died at Nice, of a diseased spine, under which he
                            had been gradually sinking. His Majesty the Emperor of Russia and her
                            Royal Highness the Princess Dagmar, of Denmark, his affianced bride, got
                            to Nice in time to witness the last hours of this amiable but ill-fated
                            youth. All Russia, the diplomatic corps, and every one who knew this
                            interesting young man, lament most sincerely his untimely end. For my
                            self I had added to the respect which I owed him as the heir of a great
                            throne and the son of a noble father, the friendship which his
                            amiability and many virtues inspired. * * * * *</p>
                <p>I have the honor to be your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C. M. CLAY.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">W. H. Seward</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State, Washington, D. C.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
